          "text": "Now I have the full picture. Let me compute the sizes analytically.\n\n**Encryption overhead:**\n- XEdDSA signature: 64 bytes appended to InnerEnvelope bytes\n- ChaCha20-Poly1305 AEAD tag: 16 bytes\n- Total: `len(postcard(InnerEnvelope)) + 64 + 16`\n\n**OuterEnvelope overhead** (fixed fields, excluding `inner_ciphertext`):\n- From golden test: 93 bytes total with 4-byte ciphertext → 93 - 4 - 1 (varint len) = **88 bytes fixed overhead**\n\n**Wire framing:** +1 byte (type discriminator)\n\nHere's the full breakdown:\n\n| Message type | InnerEnvelope (postcard) | + sig + AEAD | OuterEnvelope overhead | Wire total |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Short text \"hi\" | 46 bytes | 46 + 64 + 16 = 126 | + 88 + varint(126)=2 | **217 bytes** |\n| Text \"dag\" + DAG fields | 71 bytes | 71 + 64 + 16 = 151 | + 88 + varint(151)=2 | **242 bytes** |\n| Receipt (Delivered) | 60 bytes | 60 + 64 + 16 = 140 | + 88 + varint(140)=2 | **231 bytes** |\n| Tombstone (standalone) | N/A | N/A | N/A | **97 bytes** (1 + 96) |\n\n**LoRa MTU context:**\n- LoRa SF7/BW125 (max range): **222 bytes** payload (EU868), **242 bytes** (US915)\n- LoRa SF12 (long range): **51 bytes** payload\n- Meshtastic default: **237 bytes** (with encryption header)\n\n**Assessment:**\n\nA minimal \"hi\" message is **217 bytes** — fits within LoRa SF7 US915 (242) but tight on EU868 (222). A message with DAG fields at **242 bytes** exceeds EU868. Longer text bodies push it further.\n\nThis confirms **message chunking is necessary** for LoRa, which you already noted. The wire format overhead is reasonable — the fixed cost is ~89 bytes (outer) + 80 bytes (sig + AEAD) = **169 bytes of crypto/envelope overhead** per message, leaving only ~53-73 bytes for actual InnerEnvelope content within a single LoRa frame.\n\nFor chunking design, the key number is: **~170 bytes overhead per chunk if each chunk is independently encrypted**, or significantly less if chunking happens below the encryption layer (chunk the cipherte